        std::cout << "It's Wednesday" << std::endl;
    } else if (day == 5) {
        std::cout << "It's Thursday" << std::endl;
    } else if (day == 6) {
        std::cout << "It's Friday" << std::endl;
    } else if (day == 7) {
        std::cout << "It's Saturday" << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Invalid input. Please enter a number between 1 and 7." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we declare a variable `day` to store the user input. We prompt the user to enter a number between 1 and 7 using `std::cout`, and then we store their input in the `day` variable using `std::cin`.

We use a series of `if`, `else-if`, and `else` statements to check the value of `day` and output the corresponding day of the week. If the input matches one of the valid cases, the program outputs the appropriate message. If the input doesn't match any of the valid cases (i.e., it's less than 1 or greater than 7), the default clause of the `else` statement is executed, informing the user that the input is invalid.

